                                        <h3 id="kicker" class="kicker" role="kicker">
                                                                                            <span class="kicker-label"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180204124032/https://www.nytimes.com/pages/nyregion/index.html">N.Y. / Region</a></span>
                                                                                                                                                                    </h3>
                        			<h1 itemprop="headline" id="headline" class="headline">Pushing to Speed Up East Side Rail Link</h1>
	                                                <div id="story-meta-footer" class="story-meta-footer">
                                                                                                    

<p class="byline-dateline"><span class="byline" itemprop="author creator" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">By <span class="byline-author" data-byline-name="STEWART AIN" itemprop="name">STEWART AIN</span></span><time class="dateline" datetime="2001-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" itemprop="dateModified" content="2001-12-23T00:00:00-05:00">DEC. 23, 2001</time>
</p>

                                    <div class="story-meta-footer-sharetools">
                        <div id="sharetools-story-meta-footer" aria-label="tools" role="group" class="sharetools theme-classic  sharetools-story-meta-footer  " data-shares="facebook,twitter,email,show-all,save" data-url="https://web.archive.org/web/20180204124032oe_/https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/23/nyregion/pushing-to-speed-up-east-side-rail-link.html" data-title="Pushing to Speed Up East Side Rail Link" data-author="By STEWART AIN" data-media="" data-description="" data-publish-date="December 23, 2001">
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
<span class="sharetools-label visually-hidden">Share This Page</span>
<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad hidden nocontent robots-nocontent">
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
</div><!-- close shareTools -->
                                                                                                </div>
                            </div><!-- close story-meta-footer -->
        </div><!-- close story-meta -->
    </header>

    

        
    <div class="story-body-supplemental">
    <div class="story-body story-body-1">
        <p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="239" data-total-count="239">THE Sept. 11 terrorist attack on the World Trade Center has prompted the Metropolitan Transportation Authority to speed up work on the East Side Access Project, which would provide Long Island Rail Road riders another route into Manhattan.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="139" data-total-count="378">The project was initially scheduled for completion in 2010, but an M.T.A. spokesman said the agency now hoped to finish it by 2008 or 2009.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="448" data-total-count="826">''The incident of Sept. 11 shows the importance of East Side Access to a greater degree,'' said Kenneth J. Bauer, the railroad's president. ''If something happened at the East River tunnel, you wouldn't be able to run trains to Penn Station. The Long Island Rail Road gets 75 percent of the Nassau residents who go to New York City; 25 percent use cars. Can you imagine what it would be like if 100 percent had to use the roads to go to New York?''</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="416" data-total-count="1242">The vulnerability of the transit system was highlighted by an M.T.A. report released just after the terrorist attacks. ''It was clearly the flexibility and capacity of the subway system in Lower Manhattan that helped the M.T.A. through this ordeal,'' the report said. ''That makes more critical than ever the two important system capacity expansion projects,'' East Side Access and the Second Avenue subway projects.</p><div id="story-ad-1" class="story-ad ad ad-placeholder nocontent robots-nocontent ">
    <div class="accessibility-ad-header visually-hidden">
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</div>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-1">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="249" data-total-count="1491" id="story-continues-1">To advance the $4.3 billion East Side Access Project, the M.T.A. is to receive a portion of the $54 billion Governor Pataki requested from the federal government after Sept. 11, an M.T.A. spokesman said. He did not know how much money that might be.</p>        <a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-2">Continue reading the main story</a>
    </div><!-- close story-body -->
    <div class="supplemental first" id="supplemental-1">
    </div><!-- close supplemental -->
</div><!-- close story-body-supplemental -->
<div class="story-interrupter" id="story-continues-2">
    <div id="FlexAd" class="ad flex-ad nocontent robots-nocontent">
    <div class="accessibility-ad-header visually-hidden">
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</div>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-3">Continue reading the main story</a>
    <div class="flex-ad-creative"></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="story-body-supplemental">
    <div class="story-body story-body-2">
        <p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="285" data-total-count="1776" id="story-continues-3">Already $323 million in contracts have been awarded for the design of the project, program management and engineering work. And earlier this year, the Long Island Rail Road and the New York &amp; Atlantic Railway exchanged storage yards in a move needed to make East Side Access a reality.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="515" data-total-count="2291">The L.I.R.R. received two yards in Long Island City. During off-peak hours, they will store trains used for East Side Access during peak hours.  The yards are near what will be the entrance to the rail tunnel that will run under city streets to the existing 63rd Street tunnel from Queens to Manhattan. The upper level of that  tunnel is already being used for subway trains, and under plans for East Side Access, the lower level will be used for L.I.R.R. trains heading to Central Central Terminal over new tracks.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="308" data-total-count="2599">At Grand Central, plans call for a new L.I.R.R. terminal below the Metro-North terminal. The L.I.R.R. terminal is to include a new ticketing and waiting area, passenger concourse, four island platforms serving  eight tracks, passageways connecting to Metro-North and the subways, and new entrances and exits.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="461" data-total-count="3060">Dean Skelos, Republican of Rockville Centre, the deputy majority leader of the State Senate, stressed the importance of East Side Access not only for safety but economic reasons. ''It is critically important for the economic stability and growth of the region for it to go forward,'' he said. ''I believe there will continue to be an increase in ridership and that a quick ride into the city is important for companies staying in New York City and the region.''</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="375" data-total-count="3435">Mitchell Pally, a vice president of the Long Island Association, the region's chamber of commerce, said that his group would welcome an earlier completion of the East Side Access Project ''because the more options Long Islanders have with regard to where they are going to live and work, the better.'' The same would be true for city residents who want to work on the Island.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="242" data-total-count="3677">Senator Skelos said he came away from a recent meeting with members of the state's Congressional delegation with the belief that ''there is an opportunity for additional funding for our rail tunnels and for those in Maryland and Washington.''</p><div class="newsletter-signup hidden auto-newsletter variant-1-hidden " id="newsletter-promo" data-newsletter-productcode="" data-newsletter-producttitle="" aria-labeledby="newsletter-promo-heading">
