<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="227" data-total-count="3904">Mr. Bauer, the L.I.R.R.'s president, said that the East Side Access Project would increase the Long Island Rail Road's operating capacity by 45 percent, which he called critical because Pennsylvania Station was now at capacity.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="286" data-total-count="4190">An M.T.A. study projects that by  2010 that there will be 120,000 commuters using the Long Island Rail Road to get to Manhattan during the morning rush and that 70,000 of them will opt to use Grand Central Terminal. The L.I.R.R. currently carries 90,000 daily commuters to Penn Station.</p><div id="story-ad-2" class="story-ad ad ad-placeholder nocontent robots-nocontent ">
    <div class="accessibility-ad-header visually-hidden">
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</div>
<a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#story-continues-4">Continue reading the main story</a>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="118" data-total-count="4308" id="story-continues-4">Through November, ridership for the year was up 1.1 percent over last year, which recorded the most riders since 1949.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="235" data-total-count="4543">State Senator Caesar Trunzo, Republican of Brentwood, said he viewed the East Side Access and Second Avenue subway projects as a priority, along with safety improvements needed in the East River rail tunnels, which are owned by Amtrak.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="208" data-total-count="4751">''If a train gets stuck in there, there could be another disaster,'' he said. Improvement that are needed are more emergency exits and a new  ventilation system to pump in fresh air and remove smoke, he said.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="365" data-total-count="5116">Although the East Side Access Project is only for passenger trains, a tunnel for freight trains is also proposed. Mr. Pally of the Long Island Association said that Congress recently appropriated $5 million for an environmental impact statement for what is being called the Cross Harbor Freight Rail Tunnel, which would link Long Island to Manhattan  or New Jersey.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="175" data-total-count="5291">''It would be very beneficial for freight operations,'' he said. ''We are supportive of increasing rail access to Long Island'' because it would mean fewer trucks on the road.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="278" data-total-count="5569">Bruce A. Lieberman, the chairman of the New York &amp; Atlantic Railway, said that in the four years since his company bought the L.I.R.R.'s  freight operations, business had increased 25 to 30 percent. That translates to 12,000 to 13,000 cars of freight a year, up from 9,500 cars.</p><p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="372" data-total-count="5941">''This is a business that had 25,000 carloads in the 80's and 75,000 carloads in the 70's,'' he said, explaining that as the aerospace industry declined on Long Island, so did the need for freight service. Final figures for 2001 are not yet available, but Mr. Lieberman said that the slowing economy and the Sept. 11 attacks had had a negative effect on freight shipments.</p>        <a class="visually-hidden skip-to-text-link" href="#whats-next">Continue reading the main story</a>
    </div><!-- close story-body -->
    <div class="supplemental " id="supplemental-2">
    </div><!-- close supplemental -->
</div><!-- close story-body-supplemental -->

    
